##Amoy big garden SARS mystery: upstairs and downstairs how the spread of Faeces?

Health insight

Functional introduction, understand the health professional news

* On March 31, the The New England Journal of Medicine reported that the virus had been found in stool samples from the first confirmed patient in the United States. A similar discovery was made on Feb. 1 at the Shenzhen No. 3 People's Hospital.
* Reminiscent of the 2003 SARS epidemic, Hong Kong Amoy Gardens more than 300 cases, is spread by faecal infection.
* The Hong Kong SAR Health Department after investigation found that the real culprit to help the spread of the virus, is hidden in the toilet floor leakage, inconspicuous u-shaped trap.

On January 31, the The New England Journal of Medicine reported that the virus had been found in stool samples from the first confirmed patient in the United States. A similar discovery was made on Feb. 1 at the Shenzhen No. 3 People's Hospital.

This is reminiscent of the 2003 SARS epidemic, Hong Kong Amoy Gardens more than 300 cases, is spread by faecal infection.

Hong Kong SAR health authorities after investigation found that the real culprit to help the spread of the virus, is hidden in the toilet floor leakage, inconspicuous u-shaped trap.

Photo: yestone

On March 22,2003, a SARS case appeared in Amoy Gardens, Kowloon, Hong Kong.

This wasn't big news, as more than 100 people were already infected with SARS in Hong Kong at the time. But over the next ten days, the SARS epidemic spread like a fever through this large residential area. From March 22 to April 15, Amoy Gardens had a total of 321 cases (the final death toll was 42) , making it the worst-hit area in the world for a short-term outbreak of SARS.

Diarrhea, fever and dyspnea were common in these patients, and some died shortly after admission to hospital. More troubling, according to a survey of these patients by the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region's Department of Health, only 4 percent had been exposed to SARS patients, which was inconsistent with what was recognized at the time as the close transmission of the SARS virus through droplets.

This means that in Amoy Gardens lurks an unknown transmission mechanism through which the SARS virus can pass. For a while, Amoy big garden "poison building" name spread like wildfire.

To Stop the spread of the disease, the Hong Kong SAR issued the first quarantine order, involving a total of more than 200 households. The turnaround also happened at this time, in the exclusion of the elevator, drinking water pollution and other factors, the investigation team focused on the building's sewage treatment system.

Later investigations proved that the virus was indeed hiding in the sewage. It enters the sewage pipe through the infected person's excrement, then enters the toilet through the floor drain which has dried for a long time in other residents, attaches to the surface of the towel, the carpet and various bathroom facilities, and finally causes the human body infection, the whole chain of "fecal transmission. ".

Seventeen years later, the SARS coronavirus came from the same family as the COVID-19, showing similar transmission characteristics. Recently, academician Zhong Nanshan said, because the patient has been found in the stool of COVID-19, so can not rule out the possibility of transmission of the new coronavirus through feces.

Suspected case of SARS in Amoy Gardens

On March 22,2003, the Prince of Wales Hospital admitted a 33 year old man with chronic kidney disease who had been a regular visitor to the hospital. But this time, he had not only fever and diarrhea, but also severe respiratory distress.

The condition of a has caused the hospital to attach great importance to. Half a month ago, the Prince of Wales Hospital confirmed Hong Kong's first case of SARS, which infected dozens of health care workers with symptoms almost identical to theirs.

As a precaution, the hospital treated a and asked about his whereabouts over the past few days. A allegedly visited his brother's home in Block E of Amoy Gardens on March 14 and 19 and used the bathroom Flush toilet on both occasions.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Two days later, a's brother and sister-in-law were admitted to Hong Kong United Christian Hospital with the same symptoms and were quickly diagnosed with SARS. In the two days since, SARS cases have been reported in Amoy Gardens. As of March 26,15 patients from seven families, mostly living in units 7 and 8 of the e building, have been hospitalized.

The phenomenon immediately caught the attention of the Health, Welfare and Food Bureau. At a regular meeting on March 26, the then director, Yeoh Eng-kiong, called for an immediate investigation into the Amoy Gardens outbreak.

Amoy Gardens is a densely populated residential area with a total of 4,896 residential units surrounded by 19 buildings. Among them, the e building is 36 floors, each floor 8 units, was a cross-shaped distribution, each unit is about 48 square meters. A's brother lives on the 16th floor of this building, unit 7.

On the afternoon of March 26, Staff of the Kowloon District Office of the Department of Health in Hong Kong went on a site visit to block e of Amoy Garden. They went to the seven floors where the case occurred and questioned 20 households. At first, they determined that the virus came from a public space such as an elevator or lobby. The idea was quickly overturned when the building's cleaner took an elevator every night to collect trash, but was not infected.

Days of investigation only concluded that the source of infection in Amoy Gardens in block E, because the case here the earliest, the largest number, accounting for more than 40% of the whole community.

No progress in the investigation, but the spread of the epidemic is accelerating. As of March 30, the number of people infected in Amoy Gardens has risen to 190, including 93 in Block E. At a regular meeting on the same day, Yeoh Eng-kiong proposed to Tung Chee Hwa, then the chief executive of the district, the isolation of seat E. Tung Chee Hwa agreed and assigned the task to Margaret Chan, then the district's surgeon general.

Subsequent disclosures revealed that Margaret Chan had reservations about the quarantine plan, and that many in the Department of Health, including her, believed that Hong Kong would face intense public pressure if a quarantine order was issued. But the turn of events did not give her time to hesitate. At 6 a.m. on March 31, Margaret Chan issued a 10 day quarantine order on behalf of the Hong Kong Department of Health for Block E of Amoy Gardens. During the quarantine period, no one is allowed to enter or leave the building unless there is an official written document.

It was the first time that a quarantine order had been issued in Hong Kong since the cholera epidemic of the 1960s.

It was then that a serendipitous discovery turned things around. On April 1, the day after the quarantine order went into effect, Sarah Liao, then the head of the Environment, Transport and Works Bureau, was inspecting block e when he noticed that there was gas circulating in the building's sewage pipes and in some residents'toilets, she shared her findings with Yeoh Eng-kiong.

Yeoh Eng-kiong immediately found the situation unusual because he had just learned a few days earlier that some of the patients'stool samples contained the SARS virus. They began to suspect that the sewage system was responsible for the spread of SARS on the vertical floors of block e. For security reasons, they evacuated more than 200 residents of the e building overnight and placed them in quarantine at a resort far from the city. Sarah Liao, on the other hand, led the creation of a dedicated team to carry out a detailed investigation of the sewerage system in block e.

Four days later, Sarah Liao presented his preliminary findings in a technical report, explaining how the contaminated water produced droplets and how those droplets found their way into other homes through floor drains in the bathrooms.

At this point, suspended for half a month of Amoy Big Garden SARS finally solved the mystery. The Hong Kong SAR government released its report on April 17th, as if the real culprit was an unremarkable u-shaped trap hidden under a toilet.

A deadly U-BEND

U-SHAPED trap is a very common building in a pipe fitting, the role is to isolate the sewer air, to prevent odor into the indoor.

Block E of Amoy Gardens is designed with 8 vertical sewers, each of which collects sewage from the floors of the same unit. The water comes from floor drains in the Flush toilet, the sink and the bathroom, all of which are fitted with u-shaped traps that can only be isolated if there is enough water in the traps.

According to the survey of the residents of the e building, most residents mentioned the phenomenon of obvious odor in the toilet, reflecting the above three water trap, at least one of the problems. Flush toilet, wash basins are commonly used, these 2 water storage corner should be long-term retention of water, so the problem is likely to be in the bathroom floor on the floor drain.

According to the household survey conducted by the Department of Health Staff, most residents of Amoy Gardens are used to mopping the ground instead of washing it with water, which may easily lead to the u-shaped trap under the ground being unable to store water, doesn't isolate the foul smell from the sewer.

After the SARS outbreak, scientists at the University of Hong Kong conducted an experiment in a unit in Block E of Amoy Gardens. When the exhaust fan of the bathroom is turned on, the air pressure in the bathroom is negative and the air in the sewage pipe can be sucked into the bathroom through the floor drain. If the air in the sewer pipe contains the virus, this route is the most insidious route of transmission, which could explain why the Amoy Gardens cluster of cases in units 7 and 8 in the Vertical Direction.

But on the other hand, the flow of water from the sewer goes down, and according to this rule, the virus should also go down. In the case of the first patient on the 16th floor, he could not have infected a resident above the 16th floor through the above-mentioned route, but the real situation is that the floors with the highest concentration of infection, whether unit 7 or unit 8, are between the 13th and 24th floors, it means the virus has an upward trajectory.

An explanation for the problem, not mentioned in the findings released by the Hong Kong SAR on April 17, was supplemented a month later by a report from the World Health Organization.

When the bathroom ventilation fan is activated, the virus pumped from the sewage pipe may be carried to the patio, allowing contaminated air to pass through the open windows and into households several floors apart, the report said.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Delta plot

The architecture of Amoy Gardens has also contributed to this spread. For example, between units 7 and 8 in Block E is a narrow courtyard 1.5 metres wide. According to the aerodynamics, the air in the narrow patio is difficult to move laterally, but can move up and down quickly. Once the gas with the virus is released from the ventilation fan, it can pass through the narrow space without obstruction, which makes it possible for the virus to spread upward.

Down by the floor drain, up by the Patio, this is Amoy Garden SARS virus rapid spread of the truth.

The new coronavirus may be transmitted by faeces

Similarly, after 17 years, the probability that the new coronavirus can be transmitted through faeces is increasing.

On January 31, the The New England Journal of Medicine, a Leading Medical Journal, reported that the first confirmed case of COVID-19 pneumonia in the United States had been cured, citing the presence of the virus in stool samples taken on the seventh day of the patient's illness.

A similar finding was made on Feb. 1 by the Institute of Hepatology of Shenzhen No. 3 People's Hospital, which tested positive for COVID-19 nucleic acid in the faeces of some newly diagnosed patients.

Zhang Qiwei, a professor in the Department of Microbiology at the University of Hong Kong's School of Medicine, told the Beijing News in an interview that no live virus had been detected in the stool so far, but referring to the Amoy Garden incident, he believed that, the probability of the presence of live coronavirus in faeces is very high and the route of faecal transmission is clear.

"there will be at least two ways. One is when feces gets on a part of your pants, and then your hand touches that part, and then your nose or mouth, and you get the virus. The second is the infected toilet flush, toilet water generally have a greater impact, the feces of the virus volatilized into the air. If the toilet is closed and someone is on the side, they can get infected by breathing."

Zhang Qiwei said that although from real life, the possibility of these two ways is not high, but still can not be underestimated, especially to pay attention to public toilets, which is in line with the second way, is a very high-risk source of transmission.

The good news is that, so far, there have been no such cases as Amoy Gardens.

Previously announced in the national confirmed cases of new Crown Disease, Shenzhen and Inner Mongolia, there have been two cases of upstairs and downstairs neighbors infected with the disease, but basically ruled out the possibility of transmission through the sewage system faecal. After epidemiological investigations, the most likely cause of the infection in Shenzhen was riding in the same elevator. In the case in Inner Mongolia, the infected person, Bai, lived in the apartment of a confirmed patient, Song. Although the two had no direct contact, they had common contacts and had also been diagnosed.

Seventeen years ago, Amoy Gardens proved, at great expense, that the SARS virus could be spread through feces. Look back and hope that history will never repeat itself.
